text:
I've spent the better part of the last 15 years working in China on "sustainability", and as the video highlights, the challenges are multi-vectored, but more importantly over the next 35 years will come to scale at a speed we have never seen before.   This is why we need to move beyond "saving polar bears" and look at this challenges at the local, tangible level, and work to address the systems that are failing (like energy, food, transportation, etc).

There will be no single treaty that gets us there, in part because the growth that is mentioned will be coming from Asian and African nations where systems of infrastructure, governance, and environmental controls are largely unprepared for the shift that is coming.  

The good news is that there are models for success, and technologies that have already been proven, and are ready to deployed, and so while there are challenging times ahead, the tangibility of the crisis will force stakeholders to act together and invest.   

That is going to unleash a massive number of opportunities for mission driven entrepreneurs and organizations, whose focus is to solve the challenges urban residents face.

Without a doubt, this is a critical transition, but based on everything I have seen in China, and am seeing now in other areas of the region, the spirit of innovation and entrepreneurship is going to be the leading force for change.
